<h1>An 11-story ski hill is headed for Windsor. Can it help save an industry struggling to attract newcomers?</h1>

<p><em>Plus: Renan Ozturk is the ultimate Colorado renaissance man and a CSU student flew into a hurricane</em></p>

<!-- BYLINE -->
</mj-text><mj-table><tr style="border-top:1px solid #fcd232;border-bottom:1px solid #fcd232;text-align:left;"><td style="padding: 6px 3px;width:50px;"><img style="width:48px;height:48px;border:1px solid #fcd232;border-radius:50%; padding:0;" width="48px" height="48px" align="center" src="https://i0.wp.com/newspack-coloradosun.s3.amazonaws.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/TracyRoss_04.jpg?resize=96,96"/></td><td style="padding: 6px;"><strong>Tracy Ross</strong><br /><a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/?author_name=tracy-ross?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=SUNRISER_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email" target="_blank"><em><span style="font-size:12px;">Reporter</span></em></a></td></tr></mj-table>
<mj-text margin="0" padding="0"><h3 style="padding:.3em;font-family:'Libre Franklin','Arial Black';font-weight:700;background-color:#fcd232;font-size:24px;text-align:center;">Sneak Peek of the Week</h3></mj-text><mj-text>

<h2>Colorado&#8217;s newest ski area is a 12-acre hill east of I-25 with a 130-foot drop. Who&#8217;s excited?!</h2>

</mj-text><mj-image src="https://i0.wp.com/newspack-coloradosun.s3.amazonaws.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/IMG-6077-scaled.jpg?w=800" /><mj-text><p style="font-size:12px;font-family:'Libre Franklin',Arial,sans-serif;color:#727273;padding:0 12px;margin:0;"><em>Lifts are up and ready to haul skiers around Hoedown Hill, a new residential skiing opportunity in Windsor, where developers plan to build 3,200 homes in the town of 44,000. (Chryss Cada, Special to The Colorado Sun)</em></span></p>

<blockquote class="wp-block-quote" style="width:90%;max-width:500px;border-left: 4px double #fcd232;padding: 0px 10px;padding: 0px 10px;margin-left:0;"><span style="font-size:1.2em;line-height:1.3em;font-family:Georgia,serif;font-weight:bold;">&#8220;Everyone will feel welcome, and everyone will find something on the hill that speaks to their enjoyment.&#8221;</span><br><br><span style="font-size:1em;"><em>— Tyler Lind, developer, Raindance subdivision</em></span></blockquote>

</mj-text>
<mj-table>
	<tr style="border:2px solid white;">
	<td style="padding: 6px;text-align:center;font-size:22px;background-color:#fcd232;font-weight:bold;" width="40%">1,200 feet</td><td style="font-size:14px;padding:12px;color:#000000;background-color:#DCEEF2;" width="60%">Length of the longest of 10 tubing hills planned for Hoedown Hill</td></tr>
</mj-table>
<mj-text>

<p>For years, Colorado ski industry execs have talked about declining numbers of people wanting to put up with I-70 gridlock, shell out hundreds for lift tickets and drain the bank trying to keep the family geared up to go skiing. That gives Adrienne Saia Isaac, spokesperson for the National Ski Areas Association, hopes for little hills wanting to get into the game.</p>

<p>They&#8217;re &#8220;vital for the growth of snowsports,&#8221; through their ability to bundle gear and lessons at an affordable price &#8220;and provide terrain that&#8217;s less intimidating,&#8221; she says. So she was glad to hear about a ski hill opening in a new residential development just off I-25 near Windsor, a municipality spanning Larimer and Weld counties.</p>

<p>The subdivision is called Raindance, and the Water Valley company owns it. They&#8217;re planning to build 3,200 houses in the town of 44,000. And Lind, who is spearheading the new minimountain called Hoedown Hill, said, &#8220;We don&#8217;t feel that there is anyone we can&#8217;t accommodate. Everyone will feel welcome, and everyone will find something on the hill that speaks to their enjoyment.&#8221;</p>

<p>Which is easy to say before you try to entice skiers to hit an itty-bitty hill in a state used to shredding behemoths.</p>

<p>Lind says Hoedown will have green, blue and black runs all jammed into 12 acres and 130 feet of vertical. Add infrastructure for four conveyor lifts, including three fully enclosed and enhanced with lights and audio, that&#8217;ll service 10 tubing lanes, the longest of which will be 1,200 feet.</p>

<p>But while some Front Range skiers wouldn&#8217;t mind skipping the traffic and cost of the big resorts, they also say comparing Hoedown Hill to them is like comparing oranges and kumquats.</p>

<p>&#8220;I&#8217;d be willing to give it a try just because it&#8217;s so close and the lift tickets are so low,&#8221; said Elyse Gerke, an expert skier who attends nearby Colorado State University in Fort Collins, where campus is a 25-minute drive from the hill. &#8220;But I can&#8217;t imagine with 130 vertical feet it&#8217;s going to hold my interest for long.&#8221;</p>

<p><strong>&gt;&gt; Jump over to</strong><a target="_blank"  href="https://www.coloradosun.com"><strong> The Sun</strong></a><strong> next week to read Chryss Cada&#8217;s story on the development.</strong></p>

